## The Real Problem: Context-Blind Matching

This diagram shows a concrete scenario where the single threshold approach fails:

### The Scenario:
- Family of 4 people
- Dad and Son look similar (genetic similarity)
- Frame 1: Normal expressions
- Frame 30: Dad is smiling (changes his embedding)

### The Conflict:
When Dad smiles in Frame 30, his face embedding changes. Now the system must decide:
- Is this the same Dad from Frame 1? (Similarity: 65)
- Or is this actually the Son? (Similarity: 72)

### Why Both Thresholds Fail:

**Threshold = 70:**
- Dad's smiling face (72) is more similar to Son than to himself (65)
- System assigns Dad to Son's ID (wrong person)
- Son becomes a "new person"
- Result: 5 people detected instead of 4

**Threshold = 80:**
- Dad's smiling face (65) too different from himself
- System creates new person for smiling Dad
- Result: Dad split into 2 different people

### The Fundamental Flaw:

The system makes decisions based ONLY on similarity scores, ignoring:
- Spatial context (Dad is in same position)
- Temporal context (gradual expression change)
- Logical constraints (one person can't be in two places)
- Prior knowledge (family members look similar)

This is why multiple face swaps fail - the algorithm has no way to resolve these contradictions with a single threshold.